Okay, I hung up the new birdhouse today. This is how it looks in its new spot in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. No one asks: "What exactly is in there?"
Above is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a camera featuring a fisheye lens and an IR-LED, which I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The strange shape of this plastic box is due to the swiveling side panel of the birdhouse. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no electricity in the garden, the whole thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the gray box hanging on the side of the birdhouse, there is the battery.
When it's charged, I get about 4 hours of runtime.
That's a feature, I'd say. So the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn wouldn't have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
That's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof and point it downward into the garden.
Maybe I'll do that as well, if/when I set up more nesting boxes with cameras. Especially in areas that are further away from the house, I probably need that.
Now the camera is offline, and I don't know why. It turned off just an hour after sunset.
Possibly, the battery could not have been charged any further three hours before sunset because there wasn't enough light.
Or something less than half a day was not enough to fully charge the battery.
I guess I'll have to wait and see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry for the battery. I might have to change that in the future.
I think, in general, a few more sensors would be a good thing.
And maybe a battery that is at least theoretically capable of keeping the thing running all night.
Ah yes, and another lens.
Fisheye is quite overdone.
But I'm already looking for parts on Digikey so that I can build my own board specifically for that purpose.
Or maybe not. We'll see.
And he is still offline.
That's great.
According to the actual solar cells on the house, we only have about 90 minutes of proper sunlight.
Let's wait a bit longer, another hour or two, to see what happens—or maybe not.
Still offline.
It's never easy, after all.
It turned out that in the USB-C breakout board I used to connect the charger, the 5 V and GND were swapped on the silkscreen.
I swapped the cables, and now the charging indicator is lit.
The ESP did not go online immediately. Wait a few minutes.
An hour has passed and he is still offline.
It looks like he's restarting and triggering a Tasmota reset function.
I think the panel is useless. I've ordered a bigger one now and hope that works.
Look, what I found in my workshop.
A 24-V panel. Unfortunately, the sun is already so low (and partially obscured by a tree), that the value drops practically to zero as soon as I turn on the device.
I'll probably have to wait until tomorrow to see if this setup is sufficient or if I need the better panel I ordered.
According to Amazon, I bought the panel in 2021, and it is supposed to provide 12 V at a maximum of 1.2 A.
So either something is wrong with the panel or with my multimeter, or the data has been altered.
Good news!
You have changed the data, and the ones I have are incorrect.
The old as well as the new listing title refer to it as a 12 V 10-W panel.
Therefore, I never delete old e-mails.
Oh look! The thing went offline about an hour ago and came back online for about half a minute.
Perhaps the panel has charged the battery for just long enough to provide 38 seconds of runtime. For that, it only took a little more than two hours.
Guess what: It's cloudy today. Therefore, I'm not sure whether the (probably broken) solar panel will be able to generate enough electricity.
Wait a moment.
Update: I have installed the new panel and it seems to be working now.
It could still happen as soon as the sun sets, but let's give it a chance.
